USER INSTRUCTIONS

1. Marking your spot for picture-taking  
   1. Find an ideal spot for you to take your picture do this by:  
      1. Using the math processes outlined in the instructions find the distance needed from the ideal target. [(You can use the calculator to help you\!)](https://github.com/Duckless137/Pin-Hole-Camera)  
           
      2. Find the ideal target's vertical centering. Find a surface to set the camera on for the picture-taking process, such as tables, stools, chairs, or stands.  
         1) (to find the centering measure the vertical length and horizontal length. Find the midpoint of those lines and find where those likes converge)

         ![][image1]

      3. Mark this area for usage later using tape or spray paint.  
           
2. Loading the film and preparing the camera  
   1. First, go into the darkroom and make sure NO LIGHT is leaking in before opening the box.  
   2. Insert the film into the film holder and load the camera by:  
      1. Opening the box.  
           
      2. Removing the film holder using the ribbon string.  
      3. Grabbing the film piece and inserting it into the film holder by placing it in the space between the two cardboard slabs.  
         **![][image2]**  
      4. Inserting the loaded film holder back into the camera by placing it in the designated slot in the back of the camera.  
         **![][image3]**  
      5. Closing the camera, being careful to ensure the ribbon is hanging out the back. This should be done while making sure there is no chance of light leakage before taking the camera outside the darkroom.

3. Bringing the camera Picture spot  
   1. Accomplish this by exiting with your sealed camera and approaching the marked picture spot  
      1. Ensure you have a secure grasp of the camera. Utilizing the built-in handles on the side of the camera may help.  
4. Taking the picture  
   1. This step involves opening the aperture cover and leaving the camera in a steady and marked position for a designated period of time.  
      1. Ensure your Camera is directly centered and the correct distance from your target picture object. (Math to find these numbers are highlighted in Section III of the assembly instructions).  
           
      2. Make sure you have your timer ready and your camera is placed on a steady surface.  
           
      3. Open the aperture cover and begin to time. Do this by holding the camera with one hand and pulling on the tape tab on the aperture cover door. Press the door open and leave it. Velcro installed on the door itself will hold it open for the designated time.  
         **![][image4]**  
      4. Once your exposure time has finished, close the aperture door. Do this by holding the camera down with one hand and using the other to grab the tape tab and pull it closed.  
         **![][image5]**  
      5. Ensure both velcro seals are completely closed. Do this by applying a small amount of pressure to the door itself.

5. Bringing the Camera back  
   This step is pretty self explanatory. You’re only bringing the box to the darkroom from the place where you had taken your picture.  
   1. Pick up the box using the handles. Make sure you don’t drop the box at any point or else the box could slightly open or open entirely allowing light to leak in and ruin the picture.  
   2. Then, bring it into the dark room.  
      1. Also if others are doing the same thing as you for whatever reason, make sure there’s no one inside the dark room before you enter as it could ruin their picture that’s currently developing  
6. Removing the film for developing  
   1. After bringing the camera to the dark room and ensuring that no light is entering the room, you may open the box.   
   2. Next, use the handles on the film holder to gently take it out of the box.  
   3. Next, remove the film from the box.  
   4. Finally, have a friend or family member develop the film for you.
